04435nam a22006495i 9780300162974DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20202020ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001629747 a10.12987/97803001629742doi  a(DE-B1597)546509  a(OCoLC)1149455945  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aPQ2661.J3bP75 2010eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a843/.9142221 aAjar, Emile, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHocus Bogus /cEmile Ajar, Romain Gary. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Margellos World Republic of Letters00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAbout This Book -- tHocus Bogus -- tThe Life and Death of Émile Ajar -- tBibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBy the early 1970s, Romain Gary had established himself as one of France's most popular and prolific novelists, journalists, and memoirists. Feeling that he had been typecast as "Romain Gary," however, he wrote his next novel under the pseudonym Émile Ajar. His second novel written as Ajar, Life Before Us, was an instant runaway success, winning the Prix Goncourt and becoming the best-selling French novel of the twentieth century. The Prix Goncourt made people all the keener to identify the real "Émile Ajar," and stressed by the furor he had created, Gary fled to Geneva. There, Pseudo, a hoax confession and one of the most alarmingly effective mystifications in all literature, was written at high speed. Writing under double cover, Gary simulated schizophrenia and paranoid delusions while pretending to be Paul Pawlovitch confessing to being Émile Ajar-the author of books Gary himself had written. In Pseudo, brilliantly translated by David Bellos as Hocus Bogus, the struggle to assert and deny authorship is part of a wider protest against suffering and universal hypocrisy. Playing with novelistic categories and authorial voice, this work is a powerful testimony to the power of language-to express, to amuse, to deceive, and ultimately to speak difficult personal truths.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aBellos, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBellos, David.1 aGary, Romain, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGary, Romain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069231040uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300162974?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300162974423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300162974/original  a978-3-11-069231-0  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070474-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishb2020  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2020  aZDB-23-DKUb2020